                <h3 class="subheading">A Design That Defies Convention</h3>
                <p>The OLA Diamondhead’s design is a striking departure from anything seen on Indian roads. Its name, "Diamondhead," is a direct reference to its sharp, faceted, and minimalist aesthetic. The bike looks like it was sculpted from a single piece of material, with clean lines and an almost fully-faired body that hides its mechanical components. The most prominent design feature is the integrated front and rear lighting, which are sleek LED strips that give the bike a sci-fi feel. The absence of a conventional front fork, replaced by what appears to be a hub-center steering system, is a revolutionary design choice that promises both a clean look and potentially superior handling.<br /><br />
                    This design philosophy extends to the entire motorcycle. The handlebars are clip-on, and the footpegs are positioned for an aggressive, sport-oriented riding stance. The single-sided swingarm at the rear, a feature often seen on high-end superbikes, adds to the premium and futuristic appeal. The Diamondhead is a showcase of OLA's "Made in India" engineering and design prowess, and it is clear that they are not just building an electric bike but a symbol of technological innovation. It is a bike that will turn heads not just with its silence but with its sheer, breathtaking presence.
                </p>
                <h3 class="subheading">Expected Price and Launch Timeline: The Wait for a Game-Changer</h3>
                <p>The OLA Diamondhead is not a product of today but a vision for tomorrow. According to official announcements from OLA, the production version of the Diamondhead is a work in progress, and the company is targeting a launch date of <span class="font-weight-700">October 2025.</span> This timeline gives OLA the necessary time to refine the technology, test its components, and ensure the final product meets the high expectations it has set.<br /><br />
                    As for the price, the Diamondhead is expected to be a premium offering, reflecting its advanced technology and high-performance nature. While the initial concept had a much lower price tag, the working prototype and its advanced features have led to a revised estimate. The expected ex-showroom price is likely to be in the ballpark of <span class="font-weight-700">₹5 lakh.</span> This price point would place it in a niche segment, positioning it as a direct competitor to other high-performance electric motorcycles and even some mid-range petrol-powered sports bikes.
                </p>
                <h3 class="subheading">Deep Dive into the Expected Specifications</h3>
                <p>The OLA Diamondhead is not just about looks; it's about performance that matches its aggressive stance. The company has teased some astonishing performance figures, setting a new benchmark for electric two-wheelers in India.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Motor and Performance:</span> The Diamondhead is expected to be a performance powerhouse. OLA has hinted at a blistering <span class="font-weight-700">0-100 km/h acceleration in just 2 seconds.</span> This places it in the league of supercars and hyperbikes, a feat that would be a first for any Indian-made motorcycle. The top speed is rumored to be around <span class="font-weight-700">160-170 km/h</span>, making it one of the fastest electric motorcycles to be built in India. The motorcycle will likely use a powerful mid-drive motor, as a hub motor might not be able to achieve such high performance figures.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Battery and Range:</span> The Diamondhead is expected to be powered by OLA's in-house developed "Bharat Cell 4680" battery, a testament to the company's commitment to vertical integration. The battery capacity is rumored to be a substantial <span class="font-weight-700">7-8 kWh,</span> which would be necessary to power the high-performance motor. The true riding range on a single charge is expected to be an impressive <span class="font-weight-700">200-250 km,</span> a figure that would quell any range anxiety for riders.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Chassis and Suspension:</span> The most talked-about feature of the Diamondhead is its hub-center steering. This unconventional setup, while complex, can offer superior stability and handling. The bike is also expected to feature adaptive suspension and active ergonomics, which would allow the handlebars and footpegs to adjust for a more comfortable and in-control riding position. The frame is expected to be made from lightweight, high-strength materials like space-grade aluminum and carbon fiber to keep the weight down and improve performance.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Advanced Features:</span> The Diamondhead is not just an electric bike; it's a smart machine. It is rumored to be equipped with a host of advanced features, including a full suite of ADAS (Advanced Driver-Assistance Systems), traction control, and an integrated AI system. OLA has also teased a "Smart AR" helmet and other wearables that would seamlessly integrate with the bike, creating a complete ecosystem for the rider.</li>
                </ul>
